<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-790-724  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 790 724.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  June 21 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Korean bank signs $2.5 million software deal with BIS. (KoreaExchange Bank, BIS Banking Systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wingrove, Norman.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Korea Exchange Bank (licenses)BIS Banking Systems Inc. (contracts).andO;Product:   BIS/Midas/ABS (Banking/finance/investment software) (licenses).andO;Topic:     Sales ContractsFinancial SoftwareSoftware packages.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>KOREAN BANK SIGNS $2.5 MILLION SOFTWARE DEAL WITH BIS ADMIRALTY, HONG KONG,1990 JUN 19 (NB) -- Korea's largest commercial bank, Korea Exchange Bank(KEB), has ordered software valued at $2.5 million in the largest sale madeto date by the Hong Kong office of BIS Banking Systems.andM;KEB is licensing the BIS Midas ABS software package for worldwide use.andP;  Thesoftware will run on IBM AS/400 mid-range computers, for which BIS BankingSystems is an authorized systems reseller.andP;  It will be implemented in aninitial 10 locations over the next three years, with up to 14 more expectedto follow.andM;KEB Chairman-President, Chang-Ki Hwang, describes the system as part of KEB'sresponse to Korea's recently liberalized financial environment.andP;  &quot;I am goingto set KEB on the path to becoming a universal bank with a high profile inbanking and the securities business,&quot; he says.andP;  &quot;Only the fittest cansurvive.&quot;andM;Initial applications of the Midas package at KEB will be general ledger,treasury, capital markets, retail banking, loans and trade finance.andP;  BIS willalso supply an automatic interface between the application modules and thetelex network.andM;Six out of the initial 10 locations have already been specified.andP;  They arethe bank's Seoul headquarters and its merchant banking offices in Hong Kong,Tokyo, New York, London and Paris.andM;&quot;Korea's foreign exchange market is undergoing revolutionary changes as aresult of the internationalization of the won (South Korea's currency unit)and the liberalization of the exchange rate system,&quot; says Hwang.andP;  &quot;To developthis market as one of KEB's major profit centers we will aggressively pushplans to introduce advanced techniques in financial futures, options andswaps.&quot;andM;Bruce Quick, general manager, East Asia with BIS Banking Systems, adds: &quot;Thisorder is among the 10 largest that BIS has won worldwide.andP;  It reflects therapid development of the Korean economy.&quot;andM;(Norman Wingrove/19900620/Press Contact: Euan Barty, Euan Barty Associates,+852 529 0356)</TEXT></DOC>